  <static seed="1196" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/divideRationalExpressions50.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{y^{3}}{y^{2}-2y}} \div {\frac{1}{y^{2}+y-6}} =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>y^{2}\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right), y\ne 0\hbox{ and }y\ne 2\hbox{ and }y\ne -3</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{y^{3}}{y^{2}-2y}} \div {\frac{1}{y^{2}+y-6}} 
      \amp = {\frac{y^{3}}{y^{2}-2y}} \cdot {\frac{y^{2}+y-6}{1}} \\
      \amp = \frac{{y^{3}}}{{y\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)}} \cdot \frac{{\left(y-2\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)}}{{1}} \\
      \amp = {y^{2}\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right), y\ne 0\hbox{ and }y\ne 2\hbox{ and }y\ne -3}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>y</m> and <m>y - 2</m> were canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>y \ne {0, 2}</m>.</p>
</solution>
